p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
Have you not heard these many years ago
Jephthah was judge of Israel?
He had one only daughter and no more,
The which he loved passing well;
And as by lot,
God wot,
It so came to pass,
 As God’s will was.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
Have you not heard these many years ago
Jeptha was judge of Israel?
He had one only daughter and no mo,
The which he loved passing well;
And as by lott,
God wot,
It so came to pass,
 As God’s will was.

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
Also furthermore, who the understanding of prescience properly considereth through the same wise that anything be before wist, is said for to be coming it is pronounced there is nothing to fore wyst, but things coming, forewetinge is but of truth dpubt may not be wist, wherefore when I say the god to forewot anything, thorough necessity is that thing to be coming, al is one if I say if it shall be: but this necessity neither constraineth ne defendeth anything to be or not to be Therefore soothly if love is put to be, it is said of necessity to be, or else for it is put not to be it is affirmed not to be of necessity: not for the necessity coonstraineth or defendeth love to be or not to be [...].
[Chapter 8] Than if witting & before witting of God putteth in necessity to all things which he wot or before wot ne thing after eternity, or else after any time he will or doth of liberty but all of necessity, which thing if thou wene it be against reason not through necessity to be or not to be, all things that God wot or before wot, to be or not to be, & yet nothyng defendeth anything to be wist or to be before wist of him in our wills or our doings to be done, or else coming to be for free arbitrement.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
Also ferthermore, who yt vnderstandyng of presciēce proprelyche cōsydreth thorow the same wyse that any thyng be afore wyst, is sayd for to be cōmyng it is pronoūced, there is nothing to forn wyst, but thyng cōmyng, forewetinge is but of trouth doute may not be wyst: wherfore whā I sey yt god toforne wot any thyng, thorow necessitie is thilke thyng to be cōmyng, al is one if I sey if it shalbe: but this necessitie neither cōstrayneth ne defēdeth any thing to be or not to be Therfore sothly yf loue is put to be, it is said of necessitie to be, or els for it is put not to be it is affirmed not to be of necessite: not for ye necessite cōstraineth or defēdeth loue to be or not to be [...].
[Chapter 8] Thā yf wetyng & be∣fore wetyng of God putteth in necessite to al thinges whiche he wotte or before wotte ne thyng after eternitie, or els after any time he woll or dothe of libertie but all of necessitie, which thing if thou wene it be ayenst reason not thorowe necessitie to be or not to be, all thynge that God wot or before wot, to be or not to be, & yet nothyng defendeth any thing to be wyst or to be before wyst of hym in our wylles or oure doinges to be done, or els cōmynge to be for fre arbitriment.

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
But yet never Christian Britons so exiled
That there near some that in their privacy
Honoured Christ and heathen folk beguiled
And near the castel such there dwelt three.
That one of hem was blinde and might not see,
But it were with the eye of their mind
With which men see, after that they [have] been blind.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
But yet nere Cristene Britons so exiled
That ther nere somme that in hir priveteee
Honoured Crist and hethen folk bigiled,
And ny the castel swiche ther dwelten three.
That oon of hem was blynd and myghte nat see,
But it were with thilke eyen of his mynde
With whiche men seen, after that they ben blynde.

Be sure madame that you shall shortly see the end of him, which attendeth yet to bear so much as in him doth lie, the vehement love into another world, which maketh me to pray you to have pity on him, who (attending the rest and final sentence of his death or life) doth humbly kiss your white and delicate hands, beseeching god to give to you like joy as his is, who desireth to be,"
Wholly yours, or not to be at all.
Philiberto of Uirle.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
Nothing unto a man is miserable, if he so think it: for all Fortune is good to him, that constantly with patience suffereth it.
Plato.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
Nothing vnto a man is miserable, if he so thinke it: for all Fortune is good to hym, that constantlye with pacience suffereth it.
Plato.

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: These irrational lines and figures are the chiefest matter and subject, which is entreated of in all this tenth book: the knowledge, of which is deep, and secret, and pertaineth to the highest and most worthy part of Geometries, wherein standeth the pith and marrow of the whole science: the knowledge hereof bringeth light to all the books following, with out which they are hard and cannot be at all understood.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: These irrationall lines and figures are the chiefest matter and subject, which is entreated of in all this tenth booke: the knowledge, of which is deepe, and secret, and pertaineth to the highest and most worthy part of Geometries, wherein standeth the pith and mary of the hole science: the knowledge hereof bringeth light to all the bookes following, with out which they are hard and cannot be at all understoode.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: Now when Fame had blown abroad the possibility to obtain this Lady, such was the singular report or her surpassing beauty, that many kings and men of great nobility repaired thither. And if haply any through skill, or learning had found out the solution of the king's question, notwithstanding hee was beheaded as though he had answered nothing to the purpose: and his head was set up at the gate to terrify others that should come, who beholding there the present image of death, might advise them from essaying any such danger.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: Now when Fame had blowen abroade the possibilitie to obtaine this Ladie, such was the singular report or her surpassing beautie, that many kings and men of great nobility repaired thither. And if haply any through skill, or learning had found out the solution of the kings question, notwithstanding hee was beheaded as though hee had answered nothing to the purpose: and his head was set vp at the gate to terrifie others that should come, who beholding there the present image of death, might aduise them from assaying anie such danger.

Respice finem.
Lo here the state of every mortal wight,
See here, the fine, of all their gallant joys:
[...] Your world is vain, no trust in earth you find,
Your valyaunst prime, is but a brittle glass:
Your pleasures fade, your thoughts a puff of wind,
Your ancient years, are but a withered grass.
Mors omnibus communis.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
Respice finem.
LO here the state of euery mortall wight,
See here, the fine, of all their gallant ioyes:
[...] Your world is vayne, no trust in earth you finde,
Your valyaunst prime, is but a brytle glasse:
Your pleasures vade, your thoughts a puffe of winde,
Your auncient yeres, are but a withered grasse.
Mors omnibus communis.

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Younger Mortimer:] The haughty Dane commands the narrow seas […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Warwick:] Forslow no time, sweet Lancaster; let’s march.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Baldock:] [...] As though your highness were a school-boy still.
And must be aw’d and govern'd like a child.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[King Edward:] O, might I never ope these eyes again,
Never again lift up this drooping head,
O, never more lift up this dying heart!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasPage: 438 and 508; act 1, scene 1, line 93 and act 5, scene 1, lines 13-14.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[King Edward:] […] Frownst thou thereat, aspiring Lancaster?

[King Edward:] [And] highly scorning that lowly earth
Should drink his blood, mounts up into the air.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [King Edward:] […] I have my wish, in that I joy thy sight […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Demetrius (drawing his dagger):] This is a witness that I am thy son.
[Chiron (drawing his dagger):] And this for me, struck home to show my strength (They stab Bassianus).
[Lavinia:] Ay, come, Semiramis, nay, barbarous Tamora,
For no name fits thy nature but thy own!
[Tamora:] Give me the poniard! You shall know, my boys,
Your mother's hand shall right your mother’s wrong.
[Demetrius:] Stay, madam, here is more belongs to her.
First thrash the corn, then after burn the straw.
This minion stood upon her chastity,
Upon her nuptial vow, her loyalty,
And with that painted hope braves your mightiness;
And shall she carry this unto her grave?
[Chiron:] And if she do, I would I were an eunuch!
Drag hence her husband to some secret hole,
And make his dead trunk pillow to our lust
 [Tamora:] But when you have the honey you desire,
Let not this wasp outlive, us both to sting.
[Chiron:] I warrant you, madam, we will make that sure. -
Come, mistress, now perforce we will enjoy
That nice-preservèd honesty of yours.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Kent:] Is this the love you bear your sovereign?
Is this the fruit your reconcilement bears?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Younger Spenser:] Look up, my lord. Baldock, this drowsiness
Betides no good. Here even we are betray'd!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[King Edward:] […] Or, like the snaky wreath of Tisiphon,
Engirt the temples of his hateful head!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Marcus:] Why dost thou laugh? It fits not with this hour.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[King Edward:] […] Thy worth, sweet friend, is far above my gifts:
Therefore, to equal it, receive my heart.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[First Servingman:] Say thou wilt course. Thy greyhounds are as swift
As breathèd stags, ay, fleeter than the roe.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Petruchio:] [...] What stars do spangle heaven with such beauty
As those two eyes become that heavenly face?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Petruchio:] [...] My falcon now is sharp and passing empty,
And, till she stoop, she must not be full-gorged,
For then she never looks upon her lure.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Petruchio:] [...] Say that she frown, I’ll say she looks as clear
As morning roses newly washed with dew.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Queen Isabella:] And when this favour Isabel forgets,
Then let her live abandon'd and forlorn.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [King Edward:] Father, thy face should harbour no deceit.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Younger Mortimer:] I tell thee, 'tis not meet that one so false
Should come about the person of a prince.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Venus:] Fair flowers that are not gathered in their prime
Rot and consume themselves in little time.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
Love is a spirit all compact of fire,
Not gross to sink, but light, and will aspire.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Gaveston:] It shall suffice me to enjoy your love,
Which whiles I have, I think myself as great
As Caesar riding in the Roman street,
With captive kings at his triumphant car.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
With this she seizeth on his sweating palm,
The precedent of pith and livelihood,
And, trembling in her passion, calls it balm [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Warwick:] Tyrant, I scorn thy threats and menaces;
'Tis but temporal that thou canst inflict.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Kent:] These comforts that you give our woeful queen
Bind us in kindness all at your command.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [King Edward:] Hence, feigned weeds! Unfeigned are my woes.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richard:] Ratcliffe, come hither. Post to Salisbury.
When thou com’st thither (to Catesby) Dull, unmindful villain,
Why stay'st thou here and go'st not to the Duke?
[Catesby:] First, mighty liege, tell me your Highness’ pleasure,
What from your Grace I shall deliver to him.
[Richard:] O true, good Catesby. Bid him levy straight [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richard:] [...] Plots have I laid, inductions dangerous,
By drunken prophecies, libels, and dreams,
To set my brother Clarence and the King
In deadly hate, the one against the other [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: (The admiral discovered in bed).

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richard (to Queen Elizabeth):] Poor Clarence did forsake his father Warwick,
Ay, and forswore himself - which Jesu pardon! -
[Queen Margaret (aside):] Which God revenge!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Venus:] Art thou obdurate, flinty, hard as steel?
 Nay, more than flint, for stone at rain relenteth.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
Fondling, she saith, since I have hemmed thee here
Within the circuit of this ivory pale,
I'll be a park, and thou shalt be my deer.
Feed where thou wilt, on mountain or in dale;
Graze on my lips, and if those hills be dry,
Stray lower, where the pleasant fountains lie.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Catesby:] Rescue, my lord of Norfolk, rescue, rescue!
The King enacts more wonders than a man,
Daring an opposite to every danger.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richard:] Grim-visaged war hath smoothed his wrinkled front;
And now, instead of mounting barbèd steeds
To fright the souls of fearful adversaries,
He capers nimbly in a lady's chamber
To the lascivious pleasing of a lute.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richard:] [...] Our ancient word of courage, fair Saint George,
Inspire us with the spleen of fiery dragons.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richard:] Slave, I have set my life upon a cast,
And I will stand the hazard of the die.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Richard:] My other self, my council's consistory [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Queen Elizabeth:] Wilt thou, O God, fly from such gentle lambs
And throw them in the entrails of the wolf?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Hagges:] [...] Kill'd the black Cat, and here's the brain.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Hagges:] […] Kill'd the blacke Cat, and here's the braine.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Queen Margaret:] Earth gapes, hell burns, fiends roar, saints pray […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Anne] […] Or Earth gape open wide and eat him quick,
As thou dost swallow up this good king's blood,
Which his hell-governed arm hath butcherèd.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richard:] Up, cousin, up. Your heart is up, I know,
Thus high at least (indicating his crown), although
your knee be low.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Queen Elizabeth:] My words are dull. O, quicken them with thine! [...]
[Duchess:] Why should calamity be full of words?
[Queen Elizabeth:] Windy attorneys to their clients’ woes,
Airy succeeders of intestate joys,
Poor breathing orators of miseries,
Let them have scope; though what they will impart
Help nothing else, yet do they ease the heart.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Philip:] [...] Some twenty naked starvelings with small flints,
Hath driven back a puissant host of men,
Arrayed and fenced in all accomplements.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Philip:] [...] Some twentie naked staruelings with small flints,
Hath driuen backe a puisant host of men,
Araid and fenst in al accomplements.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Valentine:] For that which now torments me to rehearse;
I killed a man, whose death I much repent,
But yet I slew him manfully in fight
Without false vantage or base treachery.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasPage: N.p.; at the very beginning [normalized spelling].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Tom:] And if your honour please to hunt the deer,
Your hounds stands ready coupled at the door,
Who in running will o'ertake the Row,
And make the long breathed Tyger broken winded.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Tom:] And if your honour please to hunt the deere,
Your hounds stands readie cuppeld at the doore,
Who in running will oretake the Row,
And make the long breathde Tygre broken winded.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasPage: N.p.; Close to the beginning [normalized spelling].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Aurelius:] [...] But stay; what dames are these so bright of hue
Whose eyes are brighter than the lamps of heaven [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Aurelius:] [...] But staie; what dames are these so bright of hew
Whose eies are brighter then the lampes of heauen [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasPage: N.p.; a bit over halfway into the play [spelling normalized].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasPageHist: N.p.; A bit over halfway into the play.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Ferando:] [...] Yet would I pull her down and make her come
As hungry hawks do fly unto their lure.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Ferando:] [...] Yet would I pull her downe and make her come
As hungry hawkes do flie vnto there lure.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasPage: N.p.; About 3/4 into the play. [spelling normalized].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Kate:] Fair lovely lady, bright and Crystalline,
Beauteous and stately as the eye-trained bird,
As glorious as the morning washed with dew [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Kate:] Faire louely lady, bright and Christalline,
Bewteous and stately as the eie-traind bird,
As glorious as the morning washt with dew [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Speed:] Why then, how stands the matter with them?
[Lance:] Marry, thus: when it stands well with him, it stands well with her.
[Speed:] What an ass art thou! I understand thee not.
[Lance:] What a block art thou that thou canst not! My staff understands me.
[Speed:] What thou sayst?
[Lance:] Ay, and what I do too. Look thee, I'll but lean, and my staff understands me.
[Speed:] It stands under thee indeed.
[Lance:] Why, "stand under" and "understand" is all one.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Proteus:] [...] for you know that love
Will creep in service where it cannot go.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
Her lily hand her rosy cheek lies under,
Coz’ning the pillow of a lawful kiss,
Who, therefore angry, seems to part in sunder,
Swelling on either side to want his bliss;
Between whose hills her head entombèd is,
Where like a virtuous monument she lies,
To be admired of lewd unhallowed eyes.

Without the bed her other fair hand was,
On the green coverlet, whose perfect white
Showed like an April daisy on the grass,
With pearly sweat resembling dew of night.
Her eyes, like marigolds, had sheathed their light
And, canopied in darkness, sweetly lay
Till they might open to adorn the day.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Bottom:] Let me play the lion too. I will roar that I will do any man’s heart good to hear me. I will roar that I will make the Duke say "Let him roar again. Let him roar again!"

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Nurse:] [...] "Yea," quoth he, "Dost thou fall upon thy face?
Thou wilt fall backward when thou hast more wit,
Wilt thou not, Jule?"

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Helena:] Your virtue is my privilege. For that
It is not night when I do see your face,
Therefore I think I am not in the night.
Nor doth this wood lack worlds of company,
For you, in my respect, are all the world.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Romeo:] A thousand times the worse to want thy light.
Love goes toward love as schoolboys from their books,
But love from love, toward school with heavy looks.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Theseus:] But earthlier happy is the rose distilled
Than that which, withering on the virgin thorn,
Grows, lives, and dies in single blessedness.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Capulet:] [...] A hall! a hall! give room and foot it, girls.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Hermia:] Take comfort: he no more shall see my face.
Lysander and myself will fly this place.
Before the time I did Lysander see
Seemed Athens as a paradise to me.
O, then, what graces in my love do dwell
That he hath turned a heaven unto a hell!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Mercutio:] [...] He heareth not, he stirreth not, he moveth not.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Mowbray:] Setting aside his high blood’s royalty,
And let him be no kinsman to my liege,
I do defy him, and I spit at him,
Call him a slanderous coward and a villain,
Which to maintain I would allow him odds
And meet him, were I tied to run afoot
Even to the frozen ridges of the Alps
Or any other ground inhabitable
Wherever Englishman durst set his foot.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Gaunt:] [...] That blood already, like the pelican,
Hast thou tapped out and drunkenly caroused.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Juliet:] Ancient damnation, O most wicked fiend!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Juliet:] Spread thy close curtain, love-performing night,
 That runaways' eyes may wink, and Romeo
Leap to these arms, untalked of and unseen.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Capulet:] [...] At my poor house look to behold this night
Earth-treading stars that make dark heaven light.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Nurse:] Scurvy knave, I am none of his flirt-gills; I am none of his skains-mates.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Flute:] [...] Come, blade, my breast imbrue!
(Thisbe stabs herself)
And farewell, friends.
Thus Thisbe ends.
Adieu, adieu, adieu.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Carlisle:] The blood of English shall manure the ground […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Bagot:] Farewell. If heart's presages be not vain,
We three here part that ne’er shall meet again.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Lady Capulet:] I would the fool were married to her grave.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Titania:] Come, sit thee down upon this flow'ry bed,
While I thy amiable cheeks do coy,
And stick muskroses in thy sleek smooth head [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: Romeo, in the garden of the Capulet family, talks with Juliet, who is standing at the window of her bedroom.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Mercutio:] [...] Even now the frozen bosom of the north [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Bolingbroke:] My heart will sigh when I miscall it so […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Juliet:] O, bid me leap, rather than marry Paris,
 From off the battlements of any tower,
Or walk in thievish ways, or bid me lurk
Where serpents are. Chain me with roaring bears,
Or hide me nightly in a charnel house,
O’ercovered quite with dead men’s rattling bones,
With reeky shanks and yellow skulls.
Or bid me go into a new-made grave
And hide me with a dead man in his shroud.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Juliet:] At lovers' perjuries,
They say, Jove laughs.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Romeo:] Look, love, what envious streaks
Do lace the severing clouds in yonder east.
Night's candles are burnt out, and jocund day
Stands tiptoe on the misty mountain-tops.
I must be gone and live, or stay and die.
[Juliet:] Yond light is not daylight, I know it, I.[...]
Therefore stay yet. Thou need'st not to be gone.
[Romeo:] [...] I'll say yon gray is not the morning's eye;
'Tis but the pale reflex of Cynthia’s brow.
Nor that is not the lark whose notes do beat
The vaulty heaven so high above our heads.
I have more care to stay than will to go.
Come death and welcome. Juliet wills it so.
How is 't, my soul? Let's talk. It is not day.
[Juliet:] It is, it is. Hie hence, begone, away!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Romeo:] [...] Let wantons light of heart
Tickle the senseless rushes with their heels [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Egeus:] [...] Thou hast by moonlight at her window sung
With feigning voice verses of feigning love
And stol'n the impression of her fantasy
With bracelets of thy hair, rings, gauds, conceits,
Knacks, trifles, nosegays, sweetmeats [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Mercutio:] [...] (singing) An old hare hoar,
And an old hare hoar,
Is very good meat in Lent.
But a hare that is hoar
Is too much for a score
When it hoars ere it be spent.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Capulet:] Nay, gentlemen, prepare not to be gone.
We have a trifling foolish banquet towards.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Solanio:] I never heard a passion so confused,
So strange, outrageous, and so variable
As the dog Jew did utter in the streets.
"My daughter, O my ducats, O my daughter! [...]".

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Salisbury:] Therefore, to be possessed with double pomp,
To guard a title that was rich before,
To gild refinèd gold, to paint the lily,
To throw a perfume on the violet,
To smooth the ice or add another hue
Unto the rainbow, or with taper-light
To seek the beauteous eye of heaven to garnish,
Is wasteful and ridiculous excess.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [King John:] Out of my sight, and never see me more.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Costard:] O, they have lived long on the almsbasket of words. I marvel thy master hath not eaten thee for a word, for thou art not so long by the head as honorificabilitudinitatibus.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Princess:] He speaks not like a man of God his making.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Salarino:] My wind cooling my broth
Would blow me to an ague when I thought
What harm a wind too great might do at sea.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Boy:] Samson, master; he was a man of good carriage, great carriage, for he carried the town gates on his back like a porter, and he was in love.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Bastard:] [...] And you degenerate, you ingrate revolts,
You bloody Neroes, ripping up the womb
Of your dear mother England, blush for shame!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Shylock:] Three thousand ducats, well.
[Bassanio:] Ay, sir, for three months.
[Shylock:] For three months, well.
[Bassanio:] For the which, as I told you, Antonio shall be bound.
[Shylock:] Antonio shall become bound, well.
[Bassanio:] May you stead me? Will you pleasure me? Shall I know your answer?
[Shylock:] Three thousand ducats for three months, and Antonio bound.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Berowne:] And I forsooth in love! I that have been love’s whip,
A very beadle to a humorous sigh,
A critic, nay, a nightwatch constable,
A domineering pedant o’er the boy,
Than whom no mortal so magnificent.
This wimpled, whining, purblind, wayward boy,
This Signior Junior, giant dwarf, Dan Cupid,
Regent of love rhymes, lord of folded arms,
Th’ anointed sovereign of sighs and groans,
Liege of all loiterers and malcontents,
Dread prince of plackets, king of codpieces,
Sole imperator and great general
Of trotting paritors - O my little heart!
And I to be a corporal of his field
And wear his colors like a tumbler’s hoop!
What? I love, I sue, I seek a wife?
A woman, that is like a German clock
Still a-repairing, ever out of frame,
And never going aright, being a watch,
But being watched that it may still go right.
Nay, to be perjured, which is worst of all.
And, among three, to love the worst of all,
A whitely wanton with a velvet brow,
With two pitch-balls stuck in her face for eyes.
Ay, and by heaven, one that will do the deed
Though Argus were her eunuch and her guard.
And I to sigh for her, to watch for her,
To pray for her! Go to. It is a plague
That Cupid will impose for my neglect
Of his almighty dreadful little might.
Well, I will love, write, sigh, pray, sue, groan.
Some men must love my lady, and some Joan.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Gratiano:] O, be thou damned, inexecrable dog,
And for thy life let justice be accused;
Thou almost mak'st me waver in my faith,
To hold opinion with Pythagoras
That souls of animals infuse themselves
Into the trunks of men. Thy currish spirit
Governed a wolf who, hanged for human slaughter,
Even from the gallows did his fell soul fleet,
And whilst thou layest in thy unhallowed dam,
Infused itself in thee, for thy desires
Are wolfish, bloody, starved, and ravenous.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Constance:] A wicked day, and not a holy day!
What hath this day deserved? What hath it done
That it in golden letters should be set
Among the high tides in the calendar?
Nay, rather turn this day out of the week,
This day of shame, oppression, perjury.
Or if it must stand still, let wives with child
Pray that their burdens may not fall this day,
Lest that their hopes prodigiously be crossed.
But on this day let seamen fear no wrack;
No bargains break that are not this day made;
This day, all things begun come to ill end,
Yea, faith itself to hollow falsehood change!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Chatillion:] The interruption of their churlish drums
Cuts off more circumstance.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Portia:] How all the other passions fleet to air,
As doubtful thoughts and rash embraced despair,
And shudd'ring fear, and green-eyed jealousy!
"O love, be moderate, allay thy ecstasy,
In measure rain thy joy, scant this excess!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Portia:] If to do were as easy as to know what were good to do, chapels had been churches, and poor men's cottages princes' palaces. It is a good divine that follows his own instructions. I can easier teach twenty what were good to be done than to be one of the twenty to follow mine own teaching. The brain may devise laws for the blood, but a hot temper leaps o'er a cold decree [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Prince:] [...] Thy ignominy sleep with thee in the grave,
But not remembered in thy epitaph.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: Prince Hal

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] [...] Let us be Diana's foresters, gentlemen of the shade, minions of the moon [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] Why, Hal, 'tis my vocation, Hal. 'Tis no sin for a man to labor in his vocation.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] You rogue, here's lime in this sack too. - There is nothing but roguery to be found in villainous man, yet a coward is worse than a cup of sack with lime in it.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Prince:] [..] Thou art violently carried away from grace. There is a devil haunts thee in the likeness of an old fat man.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[King:] And then I stole all courtesy from heaven,
And dressed myself in such humility
That I did pluck allegiance from men's hearts,
Loud shouts and salutations from their mouths,
Even in the presence of the crownèd king.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] Hang thyself in thine own heir-apparent garters! If I be ta'en, I'll peach for this. An I have not ballads made on you all and sung to filthy tunes, let a cup of sack be my poison [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] [...] A pox of this gout! Or a gout of this pox, for the one or the other plays the rogue with my great toe.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff as King:] [...] Harry, I do not only marvel where thou spendest thy time, but also how thou art accompanied. For though the camomile, the more it is trodden on, the faster it grows, so youth, the more it is wasted, the sooner it wears.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Hotspur:] [...] he made me mad
To see him shine so brisk and smell so sweet
And talk so like a waiting-gentlewoman
Of guns, and drums, and wounds - God save the mark! -
And telling me the sovereignest thing on Earth
Was parmacety for an inward bruise,
And that it was great pity, so it was,
This villainous saltpeter should be digged
Out of the bowels of the harmless Earth,
 Which many a good tall fellow had destroyed
So cowardly, and but for these vile guns
He would himself have been a soldier.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Hotspur:] [...] and for secrecy
No lady closer, for I well believe
Thou wilt not utter what thou dost not know [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Shallow:] [...] Would I were young for your sake, Mistress Anne.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] [...] I knew you as well as he that made you.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] [...] I was as virtuously given as a gentleman need to be, virtuous enough: swore little; diced not above seven times - a week; went to a bawdy house not above once in a quarter - of an hour; paid money that I borrowed - three or four times; lived well and in good compass; and now I live out of all order, out of all compass.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Hotspur:] [...] We must have bloody noses and cracked crowns,
And pass them current too.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] Now, the report goes, she has all the rule of her husband's purse. He hath a legion of angels.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Lemot:] You must put on rich apparel, fair daintily, hear music, read Sonnets be continually courted, kiss, dance, feast, revel all night amongst gallants, then if you come to bed to your husband with a clear mind [...]
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Lemot:] You must put on rich apparrell, fare daintily, heare musique, reade Sonetes be continually courted, kisse, daunce, feast, reuell all night amongst gallants, then if you come to bed to your husband with a cleere minde

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] O base Assyrian knight [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Chorus:] […] Suppose within the girdle of these walls
Are now confined two mighty monarchies,
Whose high uprearèd and abutting fronts [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] [...] God keep lead out of me; I need no more weight than mine own bowels. I have led my ragamuffins where they are peppered. There's not three of my hundred and fifty left alive, and they are for the town's end, to beg during life. But who comes here?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] Go thy ways, old Jack. Die when thou wilt. If manhood, good manhood, be not forgot upon the face of the Earth, then am I a shotten herring.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] 'Sblood, you starveling, you elfskin, you dried neat's tongue, you bull's pizzle, you stockfish!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] By the Lord, I knew you as well as he that made you. Why, hear you, my masters, was it for me to kill the heir apparent? Should I turn upon the true prince? Why, thou knowest I am as valiant as Hercules, but beware instinct. The lion will not touch the true prince. The lion will not touch the true prince. Instinct is a great matter. I was now a coward on instinct. I shall think the better of myself, and thee, during my life - I for a valiant lion, and thou for a true prince.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Hotspur:] [...] See how this river comes me cranking in
And cuts me from the best of all my land
A huge half-moon, a monstrous cantle out.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Leonato:] [...] For, brother, men
Can counsel and speak comfort to that grief
Which they themselves not feel, but tasting it,
Their counsel turns to passion, which before
Would give preceptial med'cine to rage,
Fetter strong madness in a silken thread,
Charm ache with air and agony with words.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
Juggling Opinion, thou enchanting witch,
paint not a rotten post with colours rich.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
Jugling Opinion, thou enchaunting witch,
paint not a rotten post with colours rich.

[Walgrave:] Thy Ned, kind Ned , thine honest trusty Ned.
[...]
Enter above Marina

Enter Laurentia

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Dogberry:] [...] O, that I had been writ down an ass!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Prince:] By my troth, a good song.
 [Balthasar:] And an ill singer, my lord.
[Prince:] Ha, no, no, faith, thou sing'st well enough for a shift.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Pisaro:] I can no longer hold my patience.
Impudent villany, and lascivious Girls,
I have o'erheard your wild conversions:
You scorn Philosophy: You'll be no Nun,
You must needs kiss the Purse, because he sent it.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Pisaro:] I can no longer hold my patience.
Impudent villanie, and laciuious Girles,
I haue ore-heard your vild conuersions:
You scorne Philosophy : You'le be no Nunne ,
You must needes kisse the Pursse, because he sent it.

[Mistress Barnes:] How sir your wife? wouldst thou my daughter have
I'll rather have her married to her grave [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Coomes:] [...] I am sorry for it, I shall never see good manhood again, if it be once gone, this poking fight of rapier and dagger will come up then [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Coomes:] [...] I am sorry for it, I shall neuer see good manhood againe, if it be once gone, this poking fight of rapier and dagger will come vp then [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Benedick:] [...] May I be so converted and see with these eyes? I cannot tell; I think not. I will not be sworn but love may transform me to an oyster, but I’ll take my oath on it, till he have made an oyster of me, he shall never make me such a fool. One woman is fair, yet I am well; another is wise, yet I am well; another virtuous, yet I am well; but till all graces be in one woman, one woman shall not come in my grace. Rich she shall be, that’s certain; wise, or I’ll none; virtuous, or I’ll never cheapen her; fair, or I’ll never look on her; mild, or come not near me; noble, or not I for an angel; of good discourse, an excellent musician, and her hair shall be of what color it please God.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Dogberry:] [...]<span class="quote"> is most tolerable and not to be endured.

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Benedick:] [...] I will go on the slightest errand now to the Antipodes [...] rather than hold three words' conference with this harpy.
[...] I cannot endure my Lady Tongue.


I will be horribly in love with her!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Pisaro:] [...] To grace the mirthful complot that is laid,
Night's Candles burn obscure and the pale Moon
Favouring our drift, lies buried in a Cloud:
I can but smile to see the simple Girls,
Hoping to have their sweet-hearts here tonight [...]
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Pisaro:] [...] To grace the mirthfull complot that is laide,
Nights Candles burne obscure, and the pale Moone
Fauouring our drift, lyes buried in a Cloude:
I can but smile to see the simple Girles,
Hoping to haue their sweete-hearts here to night [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Hammon:] I chased the deer, but this dear chased me.
 [Rose:] The strangest hunting that ever I see!
But where's your park? (She offers to go away).
[Hammon:] 'Tis here: Oh, stay!
 [Rose:] Impale me, and then I will not stray.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Hammon:] I chac'd the deere, but this deere chaceth me.
[Rose:] The strangest hunting that euer I see,
But wheres your parke? (She offers to go away).
[Hammon:] Tis here: O stay.
[Rose:] Impale me, and then I will not stray.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Cassius:] "Brutus" and "Caesar" - what should be in that "Caesar"?
Why should that name be sounded more than yours?
Write them together, yours is as fair a name;
Sound them, it doth become the mouth as well [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Casca:] Nay, an I tell you that, I'll ne'er look you i' th' face again. But those that understood him smiled at one another and shook their heads. But for mine own part, it was Greek to me.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Caesar:] Cowards die many times before their deaths;
The valiant never taste of death but once.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Hostess:] [...] He made a finer end, and went away an it had been any christom child.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Eyre:] […] my fine dapper Assyrian lads [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Eyre:] […] my fine dapper Assyrian lads [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Prologue:] […] And for this small Circumference must stand,
For the imagind Surface of much land,
Of many kingdoms, and since many a mile,
Should here be measured out: our muse intreats,
Your thoughts to help poor Art [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:

For the imagind Sur-face of much land,
Of many kingdomes, and since many a mile,
Should here be measurd out: our muse intreats,
Your thoughts to helpe poore Art [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Exeter:] For government, though high and low and lower,
Put into parts, doth keep in one consent,
Congreeing in a full and natural close,
Like music.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Rose:] Here sit thou down upon this flowery bank,
And make a garland for thy Lacy's head,
These pinks, these roses, and these violets,
These blushing gilliflowers, these marigolds,
The fair embroidery of his coronet,
Carry not half such beauty in their cheeks,
As the sweet countenance of my Lacy doth.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Rose:] Here sit thou downe vpon this flowry banke,
And make a garland for thy Lacies head,
These pinkes, these roses, and these violets,
These blushing gilliflowers, these marigoldes,
The faire embrodery of his coronet,
Carry not halfe such beauty in their cheekes,
As the sweete countnaunce of my Lacy doth.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Pistol:] […] O braggart vile and damnèd furious wight,
The grave doth gape, and doting death is near.
Therefore exhale.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Brutus:] [...] There is a tide in the affairs of men [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Portia:] I prithee, boy, run to the Senate House.
Stay not to answer me, but get thee gone.
Why dost thou stay?
[Lucius:] To know my errand, madam.
[Portia:] I would have had thee there and here again
Ere I can tell thee what thou shouldst do there.
(Aside) O constancy, be strong upon my side;
Set a huge mountain ’tween my heart and tongue.
I have a man’s mind but a woman’s might.
How hard it is for women to keep counsel! -
Art thou here yet?
[Lucius:] Madam, what should I do?
Run to the Capitol, and nothing else?
And so return to you, and nothing else?
[Portia:] Yes, bring me word, boy, if thy lord look well,

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Franke:] I am not well, and yet I am not ill,
I am, what am I? not in love I hope?
In love! let me examine myself, who should I love? who did I last converse with, with Phillis: why should I love Phillis? is she fair? faith so so: her forehead is pretty, somewhat resembling the forehead of the sign of the Maidenhead Inn, et cetera. What's her hair? faith to Bandora wires, there's not the like simile: is it likely yet that I am in love? Whats next? her cheeks, they have a reasonable scarlet, never a Dyer's daughter in the town goes beyond her. Well, yet I am not in love. Nay, she hath a mole in her cheek too: Venus' mole was not more natural; but what of that, I am Adonis, and will not love. Good Venus pardon me. Let us descend: her chin, O Helen, Helen , where's your dimple Helen? it was your dimple that bewitched Paris, and without your dimple I will not love you Helen, No, yet I am safe. Her hand, lets handle that, I saw her hand, and it was lilly white, I touched her palm, and it was soft and smooth: and then what then? her hand did then bewitch me, I shall be in love now out of hand. In love! shall I that ever yet have prophaned love, now fall to worship him? Shall I that have jested at lovers' sighs now raise whirlwinds? shall I that have flouted ay-mes once a quarter, now practise ay-mes every minute? shall I defie hat-bands, and tread garters and shoestrings under my feet? shall I fall to falling bands and be a ruffing no longer? I must; I am now liege man to Cupid, and have read all these informations in his book of statutes, the first chapter, page millesimal nono, therefore, hat-band avaunt, ruffe regard yourself, garters adieu, shoe-strings so and so; I am a poor enamorat, and enforced with the Poet to say, Love o'ercomes all, and I that love obey.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Franke:] I am not well, and yet I am not ill,
I am, what am I? not in loue I hope?
In loue! let me examine my selfe, who should I loue? who did I last conuerse with, with Phillis : why should I loue Phillis ? is she faire? faith so so: her forehead is pretty, somewhat resembling the forehead of the signe of the maidenhead in, &c. Whats her haire? faith to Bandora wiars, theres not the like simile: is it likely yet that I am in loue? Whats next? her cheekes, they haue a reasonable scarlet, never a Diars daughter in the towne goes beyond her. Well, yet I am not in loue. Nay, she hath a mole in her cheeke too: Venus mole was not more naturall; but what of that, I am Adonis , and will not loue. Good Venus pardon me. Let vs descend: her chinne, O Helen, Helen , wheres your dimple Helen ? it was your dimple that bewitcht Paris , and without your dimple I will not loue you Helen , No, yet I am safe. Her hand, lettes handle that, I sawe her hand, and it was lilly white, I toucht her palme, and it was soft and smoothe: and then what then? her hand did then bewitch me, I shall be in loue now out of hand. In loue! shall I that euer yet haue prophand loue, now fall to worship him? Shall I that haue ieasted at louers sighes now raise whirlewindes? shall I that haue flowted ay-mees once a quarter, now practise ay-mees euery minute? shal I defie hat-bands, and treade garters and shoostrings vnder my feete? shall I fall to falling bands and be a ruffin no longer? I must; I am now liege man to Cupid , and haue read all these informations in his booke of statutes, the first chapter, page millesimo nono , therefore, hat-band avaunt, ruffe regard your selfe, garters adue, shoo-strings so and so; I am a poore enamorate, and enforcde with the Poet to say, Loue orecomes all, and I that loue obey.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: Iago

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Iago:] [...] O monstrous world! Take note, take note, O world:
To be direct and honest is not safe.
I thank you for this profit, and from hence
I'll love no friend, sith love breeds such offense.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Tenterhook:] Ay, but when light wives make heavy husbands, let these husbands play mad Hamlet, and cry Revenge; come, and we'll do so.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Tenter-hooke:] I but when light Wiues make heauy husbands, let these husbands play mad Hamlet, and crie reuenge; come, and weele do so.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Desdemona:] I'll watch him tame [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Othello:] O, it comes o'er my memory
As doth the raven o'er the infectious house,
Boding to all [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Othello:] [...] Pride, pomp, and circumstance of glorious war!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Iago:] Though other things grow fair against the sun,
Yet fruits that blossom first will first be ripe.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Iago:] Demand me nothing. What you know, you know.
From this time forth I never will speak word.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Iago (aside):] I have rubbed this young quat almost to the sense [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Othello:] [...] Then must you speak
Of one that loved not wisely, but too well;
Of one not easily jealous, but being wrought,
Perplexed in the extreme; of one whose hand,
Like the base Judean, threw a pearl away
Richer than all his tribe [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Bussy:] There is a deep nick in time's restless wheel
For each man's good, when which nick comes it strikes [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Bussy:] There is a deepe nicke in times restlesse wheele
For each mans good, when which nicke comes it strikes [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Lurdo:] I'll carry coals and you will, no horns, I know the law.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Lurdo:] Ile carry coles and you wil, no hornes, I know the law.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Quintiliano:] Why sir, because I entertained this Gentleman for my Antient, (being my dear friend and an excellent scholar) he takes pepper ith' nose and sneezes it out upon my Antient; now sir (he being of an uncoal-carrying spirit) falls foul on him, calls him gull openly [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Quintiliano:] Why sir, because I entertaind this Gentleman for my Antient, (being my deare friend and an excellent scholler) he takes pepper ith' nose and sneeses it out vpon my Antient; now sir (he being of an vncole-carrying spirit) fals foule on him, cals him gull openly [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Leicester:] But (madam) ere that day come,
There will be many a bloody nose, I, and and crack'd crown;
We shall make work for surgeons.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Joculo:] But madam, do you remember what a multitude of fishes we saw at sea? and I do wonder how they can all live by one another.
[Emilia:] Why soul, as men do on the land, the great ones eat up the little ones.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Joculo:] But Madam, doe you remember what a multitude of fishes we saw at Sea? and I doe wonder how thea can all live by one another.
[Emilia:] Why soole, as men do on the Land, the great ones eate up the little ones.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Marc-Antonio:] What eagles we are still,
In matters that belong to other men?
What beetles in our own?
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Marc-Antonio:] What Eagles we are still,
In matters that belong to other men?
What Beetles in our owne?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Othello:] Was not that Cassio parted from my wife?
[Iago:] Cassio, my lord? No, sure, I cannot think it [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Othello:] Indeed? Ay, indeed! Discern'st thou aught in that? Is he not honest?
 [Iago:] Honest, my lord?
[Othello:] Honest - ay, honest.
[Iago:] My lord, for aught I know.
[Othello:] What dost thou think?
[Iago:] Think, my lord? […] For Michael Cassio, I dare be sworn
I think that he is honest.
 […] Men should be what they seem;
Or those that be not, would they might seem none!
 [Othello:] Certain, men should be what they seem.
 [Iago:] Why then, I think Cassio's an honest man.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Iago:] Didst thou not see her paddle with the palm of his hand?Didst not mark that?
[Roderigo:] Yes, that I did. But that was but courtesy.
[Iago:] Lechery, by this hand! An index and obscure prologue to the history of lust and foul thoughts. They met so near with their lips that their breaths embraced together.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Othello:] [...] Honest Iago [...].(act 1, scene 2)

[Cassio:] Good night, honest Iago.(act 2, scene 3)

[Othello:] [...] Honest Iago My Desdemona must I leave to thee. (Act 1, scene 3)

[Othello:] [...] Honest Iago, that looks dead with grieving, / Speak. Who began this? On thy love, I charge thee. (act 2, scene 3)

[Othello:] No. His mouth is stopped. Honest Iago hath ta’en order for ’t. (act 5, scene 2)

(5.2.187) [Othello:] My friend, thy husband; honest, honest Iago. (act 5, scene 2)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Othello:] I had been happy if the general camp,
Pioners and all, had tasted her sweet body,
So I had nothing known. O, now, forever
Farewell the tranquil mind! Farewell content!
Farewell the plumèd troops and the big wars
 That makes ambition virtue! O, farewell!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Othello:] Give me your hand. This hand is moist, my lady.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Iago:] Were they as prime as goats, as hot as monkeys [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Hipolito:] Cursed be that day for ever that robbed her
Of breath, and me of bliss, henceforth let it stand
Within the Wizard's book -the calendar-
Marked with a marginal finger, to be chosen
By thieves, by villains, and black murderers,
As the best day for them to labour in.
If henceforth this adulterous bawdy world
Be got with child with treason, sacrilege,
Atheism, rapes, treacherous friendship, perjury,
Slander, (the beggar's sin) lies, (sin of fools)
Or any other damed impieties,
On Monday let em be delivered [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Hipolito:] Curst be that day for ever that robd her
Of breath, and me of blisse, hencefoorth let it stand
Within the Wizardes booke (the kalendar)
Markt with a marginall finger, to be chosen
By theeves, by villaines, and blacke murderers,
As the best day for them to labour in.
If hence foorth this adulterous bawdy world
Be got with childe with treason, sacrilege,
Atheisme, rapes, treacherous friendship, periurie,
Slaunder, (the beggars sinne) lies, (sinne of fooles)
Or anie other damnd impieties,
On Monday let em be delivered [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Lear:] Lend me a looking glass.
If that her breath will mist or stain the stone,
Why, then she lives.
[...] This feather stirs. She lives.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Fool:] For you know, nuncle,
The hedge-sparrow fed the cuckoo so long,
That it's had it head bit off by it young.
So out went the candle, and we were left darkling.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
I but true velour never danger sought,
Rashness, it self doth into peril thrust:
Thats only velour where the quarrel's just.
A shadow of a shadow thus you see,
Alas what substance can it be?
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
I but true velour never danger sought,
Rashness, it self doth into peril thrust:
Thats only velour where the quarrel's iust.
A shadowe of a shadow thus you see,
Alas what substance can it bee?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Hamlet:] What Coachman? My Lady's coach, for shame; her ladyship's ready to come down. (Exit Coachman. Enter Potkinn, a tankard-bearer)
[Potkinn:] 'Sfoot, Hamlet, are you mad? Whether run you now? [...]
[Gertrude:] Thank you good people. My coach for the love of Heaven, my coach? In good truth I shall swoon else.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Hamlet:] What Coachman? My Ladyes coach, for shame; her ladiship's ready to come down. (Exit Coachman. Enter Potkinn, a tankard-bearer)
[Potkinn:] 'Sfoote, Hamlet, are you madde? Whether run you now? [...]
[Gertrude:] Thanke you good people. My coach for the love of Heaven, my coach? In good truth I shall swoune else.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Albany:] [...] She that herself will sliver and disbranch
From her material sap perforce must wither
And come to deadly use.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Servant:] Here's a swaggering fellow sir, that speaks not like a man of gods making [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Servant:] Here's a swaggering fellow sir, that speakes not like a man of gods making [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Bellamont:] [...] would I were a young man for thy sake.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Bellamont:] [...] wud I were a young man for thy sake.

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Edgar:] The Prince of Darkness is a gentleman. Modo he's called, and Mahu.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Golding:] [...] the superfluity and cold meat left at their Nuptials, will with bounty furnish ours.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Golding:] [...] the superfluitie and colde meate left at their Nuptialls, will with bountie furnish ours.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Quicksilver:] Thereby lies a tale sir. The old usurer will be here instantly, with my Punk Sindefy, whom you know your Lady has promised me to entertain for her Gentlewoman: and he, (with a purpose to feed on you), invites you most solemnly by me to supper.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Quicksilver:] Thereby lyes a tale sir. The old usurer will be here instantly, with my Puncke Sindefie, whome you know your Lady has promist mee to entertaine for her Gentlewoman: and he, (with a purpose to feede on you), invites you most solemnly by me to supper.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Touchstone:] Do we not know North-north-east? North- east and by East? East and by North? nor plain Eastward?
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Touchstone:] Do wee not knowe North-north-east? North- east and by East? East and by North? nor plaine Eastward?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Follywit:] Hang you, you have bewitched me among you. I was as well given till I fell to be wicked, my grandsire had hope of me. I went all in black; swore but o' Sundays, never came home drunk but upon fasting nights to cleanse my stomach. 'Slid, now I'm quite altered, blown into light colors, let out oaths by th' minute, sit up late till it be early, drink drunk till I am sober, sink down dead in a tavern, and rise in a tobacco shop. Here's a transformation [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Follywit:] Hang you, you haue bewitcht me among you, I was as well giuen till I fell to be wicked, my Grandsire had hope of me, I went all in blacke, swore but a Sundaies, neuer came home drunke, but vpon fasting nights to clense my stomacke; sl'id now I'me quite altered, blowne into light colours, let out othes by'th minute, sit vp late till it bee early, drinke drunke till I am sober, sincke downe dead in a Tauerne, and rise in a Tabacco-shop: her's a transformation [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:

To drown with billows of overwhelming woes.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:

To drowne with Billows of orewhelming woes.

And here the son was his old Father's death […].

And heere the Sonne was his old Fathers death […].

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Caesar:] When Phoebus left fair Thetis' watery couch,
And peeping forth from out the golden gate
Of his bright palace saw our battle rank'd:
Off did he seek to turn his fiery steeds […].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Cæsar:] When Phæbus left faire Thetis watery couch,
And peeping forth from out the goulden gate
Of his bright pallace saw our battle rank'd:
Oft did hee seeke to turne his fiery steeds […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Pompey:] [...] 'Tis but thy fear that doth it so miscall.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Pompey:] […] Tis but thy feare that doth it so miscall.

Consume me fire with thy devouring flames […].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Pompey:] Earth gape and swallow him that Heauens hate,
Consume me Fire with thy deuouring flames […].

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Caesar:] […] Unto those sands where high erected posts
Of great Alcides, do uphold his name […].

Of great Alcides , do vp hold his name […].

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Caesar:] […] He on his golden trapped Palfreys rides,
That from their nostrils do the morning blow […].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Caesar:] […] He on his goulden trapped Palfreys rides,
That from their nostrels do the morning blow […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Paroles:] My meaning in 't, I protest, was very honest in the behalf of the maid, for I knew the young count to be a dangerous and lascivious boy, who is a whale to virginity and devours up all the fry it finds.

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:

Yet Pompey once was even as great as he,
And how he rode clad in stories' spoils […].

[Anthony:] Though Caesar be as great as great may be,

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Gertrude:] And draw all my servants in my bow, and keep my counsel, and tell me tales, and put me riddles, and read on a book sometimes when I am busy, and laugh at country gentlewomen, and command anything in the house for my retainers; and care not what you spend, for it is all mine; and, in any case, be still a maid, whatsoever you do, or whatsoever any man can do unto you.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Edmund:] [...] When my dimensions are as well compact,
My mind as generous and my shape as true [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Count:] Lazarello, bestir thy self nimbly and soddenly, and hear me with patience.
[Lazarello:] Let me not fall from myself; speak I am bound to hear.
[Count:] So art thou to revenge, when thou shalt hear.
The fish head is gone, and we know not whither.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Captain:] Doubtful it stood,
 As two spent swimmers that do cling together
And choke their art.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Ross:] From Fife, great king,
Where the Norweyan banners flout the sky
And fan our people cold [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Captain:] Yes, as sparrows eagles, or the hare the lion.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[First Witch:] He knows thy thought.
 Hear his speech but say thou naught.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Ventidius:] O, Silius, Silius,
I have done enough. A lower place, note well,
May make too great an act. For learn this, Silius:
Better to leave undone than by our deed
Acquire too high a fame when him we serve 's away. [...] The soldier's virtue, rather makes choice of loss
Than gain which darkens him.
I could do more to do Antonius good,
But 'twould offend him. And in his offense
Should my performance perish.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Ross:] And Duncan's horses (a thing most strange and certain),
Beauteous and swift, the minions of their race,
Turned wild in nature, broke their stalls, flung out,
Contending 'gainst obedience, as they would
Make war with mankind.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Charmian:] Nay, if an oily palm be not a fruitful prognostication, I cannot scratch mine ear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [First Witch:] But in a sieve I'll thither sail [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Lady Macbeth:] It was the owl that shrieked, the fatal bellman,
Which gives the stern'st good-night.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Lingua:] Witness this lie, Mendacio's with me now,
But sirrah out of jesting will they come?
[Mendacio:] Yes and it like your Ladyship presently:
Here may you have me prest to flatter them.
[Lingua:] I'll flatter no such proud Companions,
'Twill do no good, therefore I am determined
To leave such baseness.
[Mendacio:] Then shall I turn and bid them stay at home.
[Lingua:] No, for their coming hither to this grove,
Shall be a means to further my devise,
Therefore I pray thee Mendacio go presently,
Run you vile Ape.
[Mendacio:] Whether?
[Lingua:] What dost thou stand?
[Mendacio:] Till I know what to do.
[Lingua:] S'precious 'tis true,
So might thou finely o'er-run thine errand.
Hast to my Chest.
[Mendacio:] Ay, ay,
[Lingua:] There shalt thou find,
A gorgeous Robe, and golden Coronet,
Convey them hither nimbly, let none see them.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Lingua:] Witnesse this lye, Mendacio's with me now,
But sirra out of iesting will they come?
[Mendacio:] Yes and it like your Ladyship presently:
Here may you haue me prest to flatter them.
[Lingua:] Ile flatter no such proud Companions,
'Twill doe no good, therefore I am determined
To leaue such basenesse.
[Mendacio:] Then shall I turne and bid them stay at home.
[Lingua:] No, for their comming hither to this groue,
Shall be a meanes to further my deuise,
Therefore I pray thee Mendacio go presently,
Run you vile Ape.
[Mendacio:] Whether?
[Lingua:] What doost thou stand?
[Mendacio:] Till I know what to doe.
[Lingua:] S'pretious 'tis true,
So might thou finely ore-run thine errand.
Hast to my Chest.
[Mendacio:] I, I,
[Lingua:] There shalt thou find,
A gorgeous Robe, and golden Coronet,
Conuey them hither nimbly, let none see them.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Pericles:] O, Helicanus! Strike me, honored sir.
Give me a gash, put me to present pain,
Lest this great sea of joys rushing upon me
O'erbear the shores of my mortality
And drown me with their sweetness.
