p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Grumio:] Out of their saddles into the dirt, <span class="quote">and thereby hangs a tale.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: Clim of the Clough [the devil] thou that usest to drink nothing but scalding lead and sulphur in hell, thou art not so greedy of thy night gear. O, but thou hast a foul swallow, if it come once to carousing of human blood; but that's but seldom [...] otherwise thou art tide at rack and manger, and drinkest nothing but the Aqua vitae of vengeance all thy life time [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: Clim of the Clough [the devil] thou that vsest to drinke nothing but scalding lead and sulpher in hell, thou art not so greedie of thy night geare. O, but thou hast a foule swallow, if it come once to carousing of humane bloud; but thats but seldom [...] otherwise thou art tide at rack and manger, and drinkest nothing but the Aqua vitae of vengeance all thy life time [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [...] the heavy headed gluttonous house-dove [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [...] the heauie headed gluttonous house-doue [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
Sloth and sluggish security [...].

[...] neglect [...] dallying [...] indignities [...] love-dream [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: Sloth and sluggish securitye [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: I will not forget the old wives logick, when Adam delved and Eve spanne, who was then a Gentleman?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Duke:] [...] Go, some of you, knock at the abbey gate [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasPage: 439; act 1, scene 1, line 134, act 1, scene 1, line 161 and act 2, scene 2, line 72.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Edward:] I cannot brook these haughty menaces […]

[Edward:] Cease brother, for I cannot brook these words […]

[Gaveston:] My Lord I cannot brook these iniuries.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: A mighty deformer of men's manners and features, is this unnecessary vice of all other. Let him be indued with never so many virtues, and have as much goodly proportion and favour as nature can bestow upon a man; yet if he be thirsty after his own destruction, and hath no joy nor comfort, but when he is drowning his soul in a gallon pot, that one beastly imperfection will utterly obscure all that is commendable in him; and all his good qualities sink like lead down to the bottom of his carousing cups, where they will lie, like lees and dregs, dead and unregarded of any man.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: A mightie deformer of mens manners and features, is this vnnecessary vice of all other. Let him bee indued with neuer so many vertues, and haue as much goodly proporton and fauour as nature can bestow vppon a man; yet if he bee thirstie after his owne destruction, and hath no ioy nor comfort, but when he is drowning his soule in a gallon pot, that one beastly imperfection will vtterlie obscure all that is commendable in him; and all his good qualities sinke like lead down to the bottome of his carrowsing cups, where they will lie, like lees and dregges, dead and vnregarded of any man.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: For besides, nature hath left him a flaberkin face, like one of the four winds, and cheeks that sag like a woman's dugs over his chin-bone, his apparel is so put up with bladders of Taffeta, and his back like beef stuffed with Parsley, so drawn out with Ribands and deuces, and blistered with light sarcenet bastings, that you would think him [a Dane] nothing but a swarm of Butterflies, if you saw him a far off.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: For besides, nature hath left him a flaberkin face, like one of the foure winds, and cheeks that sag like a womans dugs ouer his chin-bone, his apparel is so put vp with bladders of Taffatie, and his back like biefe stuft with Parsly, so drawne out with Ribands and deusies, and blisterd with light sarcenet bastings, that you would think him [a Dane] nothing but a swarme of Butterflies, if you saw him a farre off.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: The Danes are bursten-bellied sots, that are to be confuted with nothing but Tankards or quart-pots, and Ovid might as well have read his verses to the Geese that understood him not, as a man talk reason to them that have no ears but their mouths nor sense but of that which they swallow down their throats. God so love me, as I love the quick-witted Italians, and therefore love them more, because they mortally detest this surley swinish Generation.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: The Danes are bursten-bellied sots, that are to bee confuted with nothing but Tankards or quart-pots, and Ouid might as well haue read his verses to the Getes that vnderstood him not, as a man talk reason to them that haue no eares but their mouths nor sense but of that which they swallowe downe their thrates. God so loue me, as I loue te quick-witted Italians, and therefore loue them more, because they mortally detest this surley swinish Generation.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: Men when they are idle, and know not what to do, saith one let us go to the Steelyard and drink Rhenish wine. Nay, if a man knew where a good whorehouse were saith another, it were somwhat like. Nay saith the third, let us go to a dicing-house or a bowling alley, and there we shall have some sport for our money.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: Men when they are idle, and know not what to do, saith one let vs go to the Stilliard and drink Rhenish wine. Nay, if a man knew where a good whorhouse were saith another, it were somwhat like. Nay saith the third, let vs go to a dicing-house or a bowling alley, and there we shall haue some sport for our money.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: Besides, my vagrant Reveller haunts Plays, & sharpens his wits with frequenting the company of Poets; he emboldens his blushing face by courting fair women on the sudden, and look into all Estates, by conversing with them in public places. Now tell me whether of these two, the heavy-headed gluttonous house dove, or this lively wanton young Gallant, is likely to prove the wiser man, and better member in the Common-wealth.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: Besides, my vagrant Reueller haunts Plaies, & sharpens his wits with frequenting the company of Poets; he emboldens his blushing face by courting fair women on the sodaine, and looke into all Estates, by conversing with them in publike places. Nowe tell me whether of these two, the heauie-headed gluttonous house doue, or this liuelie wanton yoong Gallant, is likely to prooue the wiser man, and better member in the Common-wealth.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: Sloth in Nobility, Courtiers, Scholars, or any men is the chiefest cause that brings them in contempt. For as industry and unfatigable toil raiseth mean persons from obscure houses to high thrones of authority: so Sloth and sluggish security causeth proud Lords to tumble from the towers of their starry descents, and be trodden underfoot of every inferior Bosnian. […] The only enemy to Sloth is contention and emulation; as propose one man to myself, that is the only mirror of our Age, and strive to out-go him in virtue.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: Sloth in Nobilitie, Courtiers, Schollers, or any men is the chiefest cause that brings them in contempt. For as industrie and vnfatigable toyle rayseth meane persons from obscure houses to high thrones of authoritie: so Sloth and sluggish securitye causeth proud Lords to tumble from the towers of their starriediscents, and be trodden vnderfoot of euery inferiour Besonian. […] The only enemy to Sloth is contention and emulation; as propose one man to myselfe, that is the onely mirrour of our Age, and striue to out-go him in vertue.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: That is the course he that will be popular must take, which if he neglect, and sit dallying at home, nor will be awaked by any indignities out of his love-dream, but suffer every upstart groom to defy him, set him at naught, and shake him by the beard unrevenged, let him straight take orders and be a Churchman, and then his patience may pass for a virtue, but otherwise he shall be suspected of cowardice, and not car'd for of any.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: That is the course he that will be popular must take, which if he neglect, and sit dallying at home, nor will be awakt by any indignities out of his loue-dreame, but suffer every vpstart groome to defie him, set him at naught, and shake him by the beard vnreuengde, let him straight take orders and be a Church-man, and then his patience may passe for a vertue, but otherwise he shall be suspected of cowardise, and not car'd for of any.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Edward:] [...] Gallop apace, bright Phoebus, through the sky,
And, dusky Night, in rusty iron car [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Saturninus:] [...] My lords, you know, as know the mightful gods,
However these disturbers of our peace
Buzz in the people's ears, there naught hath passed
But even with law against the willful sons
Of old Andronicus.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Younger Mortimer:] [...] Farewell, fair queen. Weep not for Mortimer,
That scorns the world, and, as a traveller,
Goes to discover countries yet unknown.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Young Lucius:] Grandsire, 'tis Ovid's Metamorphosis.
 My mother gave it me.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[King Richard:] For God's sake, let us sit upon the ground
And tell sad stories of the death of kings -
How some have been deposed, some slain in war […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[King Richard:] Let me unkiss the oath twixt thee and me;
And yet not so, for with a kiss 'twas made. -
Part us, Northumberland […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[York:] […] Mounted upon a hot and fiery steed,
Which his aspiring rider seemed to know […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Ghosts of Princes:] Sleep, Richmond, sleep in peace and wake in joy.
Good angels guard thee from the boar's annoy.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richard:] Go, gentlemen, every man unto his charge.
Let not our babbling dreams affright our souls.
Conscience is but a word that cowards use,
Devised at first to keep the strong in awe.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Gaunt:] Things sweet to taste prove in digestion sour.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richard:] Thou sing’st sweet music. Hark, come hither, Tyrrel.
Go, by this token. Rise, and lend thine ear.
There is no more but so. Say it is done,
And I will love thee and prefer thee for it.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Buckingham:] My hair doth stand an end to hear her curses.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: To the most honoured and virtuous, beautified lady, the lady Elizabeth Carey
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: To the most honored, and vertvuovs beavtified ladie the ladie Elizabeth Carey

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richard:] He was the right, and so indeed it is.
Tell the clock there. Give me a calendar.
Who saw the sun today?
 [Ratcliffe:] Not I, my lord.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richmond:] The father rashly slaughtered his own son;
The son, compelled, been butcher to the sire.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richard:] Give me another horse! Bind up my wounds!
Have mercy, Jesu! - Soft, I did but dream.
O coward conscience, how dost thou afflict me!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Duchess:] Dead life, blind sight, poor mortal living ghost,
Woe’s scene, world’s shame, grave’s due by life usurped,
Brief abstract and record of tedious days,
 Rest thy unrest on England’s lawful earth,
Unlawfully made drunk with innocent blood.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
I have a fine bow, and an ivory arrow:
And if thou miss, yet meat thou shalt lack,
I'll hang a bag and bottle at thy back.

Wilt thou set springs in a frosty Night,
To catch the long-billed Woodcock and the Snipe?
(By the bright glimmering of the Starry light)
The Partridge, Phaesant, or the greedy Crype?
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
I haue a fine bowe, and an yuorie arrow:
And if thou misse, yet meate thou shalt lacke,
Ile hang a bag and bottle at thy backe.

Wilt thou set springes in a frostie Night,
To catch the long-billd Woodcocke and the Snype?
(By the bright glimmering of the Starrie light)
The Partridge, Phaesant, or the greedie Crype?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: Bonny Sweet Robin

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [...] because they fear not death, they should fear something after death [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [...] because they feare not death, they sholde feare somethinge after death [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
For princes are the glass, the school, the book,
Where subjects' eyes do learn, do read, do look.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: A most vain thing it is in many universities at this day, that they count him excellent eloquent, who stealeth not whole phrases but whole pages out of Tully. If of a number of shreds of his sentences he can shape an oration, from all the world he carries it away, although in truth it be no more than a fool's coat of many colours.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: A most vaine thing it is in many vniversities at this daie, that they count him excellent eloquent, who stealeth not whole phrases but whole pages out of Tully. If of a number of shreds of his sentences he can shape an oration, from all the world he carries it awaie, although in truth it be no more than a fooles coat of many colours.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Mercutio:] For this driveling love is like a great natural that runs lolling up and down to hide his bauble in a hole.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Juliet:] How camest thou hither, tell me, and wherefore?
The orchard walls are high and hard to climb,
And the place death, considering who thou art,
If any of my kinsmen find thee here.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Nurse:] There's no trust
No faith, no honesty in men.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Mowbray:] [...] And now my tongue's use is to me no more
Than an unstringèd viol or a harp, up
Or, being open, put into his hands
That knows no touch to tune the harmony.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Richard:] Must I do so? And must I ravel out
My weaved-up follies?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Bolingbroke:] Go, some of you, and fetch a looking-glass.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasPage: Act 1, scene 1, lines 71-73 and act 5, scene 3, line 70.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Tybalt:] What, drawn and talk of peace? I hate the word
As I hate hell, all Montagues, and thee.
Have at thee, coward!

[Romeo:] Wilt thou provoke me? Then have at thee, boy!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Nurse:] [...] I do bear a brain.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Nurse:] [...] if you should lead her into a fool's paradise, as they say, it were a very gross kind of behavior, as they say.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Romeo:] See how she leans her cheek upon her hand.
O, that I were a glove upon that hand,
 That I might touch that cheek!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Nurse:] Even or odd, of all days in the year
 Come Lammas Eve at night shall she be fourteen. [...]
And she was weaned (I never shall forget it)
Of all the days of the year, upon that day.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Gardener:] Poor queen, so that thy state might be no worse,
I would my skill were subject to thy curse.
Here did she fall a tear. Here in this place
I'll set a bank of rue, sour herb of grace.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [First Watch:] Go, some of you; whoe'er you find, attach.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Bolingbroke:] Go, some of you, convey him to the Tower.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Mercutio:] [...] Now will he sit under a medlar tree
And wish his mistress were that kind of fruit
As maids call medlars when they laugh alone.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Mercutio:] [...] O Romeo, that she were, O, that she were
An open-arse, thou a pop'rin pear.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Oberon:] [...] So shall all the couples three
Ever true in loving be,
And the blots of Nature's hand
Shall not in their issue stand.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Romeo:] […] Dry sorrow drinks our blood.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Lady Capulet:] Ay, sir, but she will none, she gives you thanks.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Lysander:] [...] I have a widow aunt, a dowager
Of great revenue, and she hath no child.
From Athens is her house remote seven leagues,
And she respects me as her only son.
There, gentle Hermia, may I marry thee;
And to that place the sharp Athenian law
Cannot pursue us.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Juliet:] Too like the lightning, which doth cease to be
Ere one can say "It lightens."

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Benvolio:] He swung about his head, and cut the winds,
Who, nothing hurt withal, hiss'd him in scorn.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Capulet:] Wife, we scarce thought us blessed
That God had lent us but this only child,
But now I see this one is one too much,
And that we have a curse in having her.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Oberon:] [...] And this ditty, after me
Sing and dance it trippingly.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: Romeo and Juliet

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Friar:] And nought so rich on either rock or shelf,
But, if unknown, lies uselesse to it self.
Therefore who thus doth make their secrets known,
Doth profit others, and not hurt his own.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Prince:] For never was a story of more woe
Than this of Juliet and her Romeo.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[York:] I have had feeling of my cousin's wrongs
And labored all I could to do him right.
But in this kind to come, in braving arms,
Be his own carver and cut out his way
To find out right with wrong, it may not be.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Juliet:] O, bid me leap, rather than marry Paris,
From off the battlements of any tower,
Or walk in thievish ways, or bid me lurk
Where serpents are. Chain me with roaring bears,
Or hide me nightly in a charnel house,
/ O’ercovered quite with dead men’s rattling bones,
With reeky shanks and yellow chapless skulls.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Prologue:] [...] From forth the fatal loins of these two foes
A pair of star-crossed lovers take their life;
Whose misadventured piteous overthrows
Doth with their death bury their parents' strife.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
But if these eyes of yours, (load-stars of Love,
Showing the World's great dance to your mind's eye!)
Cannot with all their demonstrations move
Kind apprehension in your fantasy,
Of dancing's virtue, and nobility:
How can my barbarous tongue win you there to
Which Heau'n and Earth's fair speech could never do?
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
But if these eyes of yours, (load-starrs of Loue,
Shewing the World's great daunce to your mind's eye!)
Cannot with all their demonstrations moue
Kinde apprehension in your fantasie,
Of Dauncing's vertue, and nobilitie:
How can my barbarous tongue win you there to
Which Heau'n and Earth's faire speech could neuer do?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[King:] Berowne is like an envious sneaping frost
That bites the firstborn infants of the spring.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: Let us therefore pray that we be not miscarried by the deceits of the wicked pilot Satan, whose directions are merely indirect, and whose sails are deceitful, being glorious to the eye; and the bark wherein he carrieth his unhappy passengers seemeth to be a most secure cradle, gliding on without tempest or wave, until it come to the end of their race, where, alas! they fall into the gulf of perpetual perdition. Such a master is he, and such mariners are his false prophets, that they delight flesh and blood, and all their course seemeth sweet, but short: and sour merchandise shall they have, that pass in the pinnace of his poisoned errors.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Armado:] Call’st thou my love "hobby-horse"?
[Boy:] No, master. The hobby-horse is but a colt, and your love perhaps a hackney.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Pandulph:] The better act of purposes mistook
Is to mistake again; though indirect,
Yet indirection thereby grows direct,
And falsehood falsehood cures, as fire cools fire
Within the scorchèd veins of one new-burned.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [King Philip:] It likes us well.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Catechysius the Hermit:] Now all is but the action of the Mind,
That rectifi'd, the rest is all but wind.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Bastard:] By heaven, these scroyles of Angiers flout you, kings,
And stand securely on their battlements
As in a theater, whence they gape and point
At your industrious scenes and acts of death.
Your royal presences, be ruled by me:
Do like the mutines of Jerusalem,
Be friends awhile, and both conjointly bend
Your sharpest deeds of malice on this town.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Portia:] [...] [I'll] prove the prettier fellow of the two,
And wear my dagger with the braver grace,
And speak between the change of man and boy
With a reed voice, and turn two mincing steps
Into a manly stride, and speak of frays
Like a fine bragging youth, and tell quaint lies
How honorable ladies sought my love,
Which I denying, they fell sick and died -
I could not do withal! - then I'll repent,
And wish, for all that, that I had not killed them.
And twenty of these puny lies I'll tell,
That men shall swear I have discontinued school
Above a twelvemonth.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Berowne:] [...] Well, I do nothing in the world but lie, and lie in my throat.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [King:] [...] But to the place where. It standeth north-north-east and by east from the west corner of thy curious-knotted garden. There did I see that low-spirited swain, that base minnow of thy mirth [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[King Philip:] [...] Our cannons' malice vainly shall be spent
Against th'invulnerable clouds of heaven.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Berowne:] But love, first learnèd in a lady’s eyes,
Lives not alone immurèd in the brain,
But with the motion of all elements
Courses as swift as thought in every power,
And gives to every power a double power,
Above their functions and their offices.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Pembroke:] Indeed, we heard how near his death he was
Before the child himself felt he was sick.
This must be answered either here or hence.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: The proper end of conscience is, to determin of things done. And by this one thing, conscience is distinguished from all other gifts of the mind as intelligence opinion, science faith, prudence. Intelligence simply conceives a thing to be or not to be: science judgeth it to be certain and sure: faith is a persuasion, whereby we believe things that are not [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: The proper ende of conscience is, to determine of things done. And by this one thing, conscience is distinguished from all other gifts of the mind as intelligence opinion, science faith, prudence. Intelligence simply conceives a thing to be or not to be: science iudgeth it to be certen and sure: faith is a perswasion, whereby we beleeue things that are not [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] Now, my masters, happy man be his dole, say I. Every man to his business.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Shallow:] Bodykins, Master Page, though I now be old and of the peace, if I see a sword out, my finger itches to make one.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Hostess Quickly:] No, thou arrant knave. I would to God that I might die, that I might have thee hanged. Thou hast drawn my shoulder out of joint.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] What, upon compulsion? Zounds, an I were at the strappado or all the racks in the world, I would not tell you on compulsion. Give you a reason on compulsion? If reasons were as plentiful as blackberries, I would give no man a reason upon compulsion, I.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Falstaff:] Will you tell me, Master Shallow, how to choose a man? Care I for the limb, the thews, the stature, bulk, and big assemblance of a man! Give me the spirit, Master Shallow.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Fallstaff:] [sings] When Arthur first in court -
[To Will] Empty the Jordans [Will exits]
And was a worthy king -

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Shallow:] Yea, Davy, I will use him well. A friend i' th' court is better than a penny in purse. Use his men well, Davy, for they are arrant knaves and will backbite.
[Davy:] No worse than they are back-bitten, sir, for they have marvelous foul linen.
[Shallow:] Well-conceited, Davy. About thy business, Davy.
[Davy:] I beseech you, sir, to countenance William Visor of Woncot against Clement Perkes o’ th’ hill.
[Shallow:] There is many complaints, Davy, against that Visor. That Visor is an arrant knave, on my knowledge.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Comedy:] How some damned tyrant to obtain a crown,
Stabs, hangs, poisons, smothers, cuts throats,
And then a Chorus too comes howling in,
And tells us of the worrying of a cat,
Then of a filthy whining ghost,
Lapt in some foul sheet, or a leather pelt,
Comes screaming like a pig half sticked,
And cries Vindicta, revenge, revenge:
With that a little rose flashes forth,
Like smoke out of a Tobacco pipe, or a boys squib:
Then comes in two or three like to drovers,
With tailors bodkins, stabbing one another,
Is not this trim? is not here goodly things?
That you should be so much accounted of,
I would not else.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Comedy:] How some damnd tyrant to obtaine a crowne,
Stabs, hangs, impoysons, smothers, cutteth throats,
And then a Chorus too comes howling in,
And tels vs of the worrying of a cat,
Then of a filthie whining ghost,
Lapt in some fowle sheete, or a leather pelch,
Comes skreaming like a pigge halfe stickt,
And cries Vindicta, reuenge, reuenge:
With that a little Rosen flasheth forth,
Like smoke out of a Tabacco pipe, or a boyes squib:
Then comes in two or three like to drouers,
With taylers bodkins, stabbing one another,
Is not this trim? is not here goodly things?
That you should be so much accounted of,
I would not else.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[King:] [...] Let all the tears that should bedew my hearse
Be drops of balm to sanctify thy head;
Only compound me with forgotten dust.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Glendower:] I cannot blame him. At my nativity
The front of heaven was full of fiery shapes,
Of burning cressets, and at my birth
The frame and huge foundation of the Earth
 Shaked like a coward.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Hotspur:] And I can teach thee, coz, to shame the devil
By telling truth. Tell truth and shame the devil.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Dogberry:] I leave an arrant knave with your Worship, which I beseech your Worship to correct yourself, for the example of others.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Bobadill:] […] sure I was struck with a planet thence, for I had no power to touch my weapon.
[Ed. Knowell:] I, like enough, I have heard of many that have been beaten under a planet: go, get you to a surgeon.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Bobadill:] […] sure I was strooke with a plannet thence, for I had no power to touch my weapon.
[Ed. Kno’well:] I, like inough, I haue heard of many that haue beene beaten vnder a plannet: goe, get you to a surgean.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Benedick:] And do it with all thy heart.
[Beatrice:] I love you with so much of my heart that none is left to protest.
[Benedick:] Come, bid me do anything for thee.
[Beatrice:] Kill Claudio.
[Benedick:] Ha! Not for the wide world.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Margaret:] Well, an you be not turned Turk, there's no more sailing by the star.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Verges:] Marry, sir, our watch tonight, excepting your Worship's presence, ha' ta'en a couple of as arrant knaves as any in Messina.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
From the black kingdom of infernal Dis [...]
And from the dungeon of the dark abyss,
Wherein the Ocean Seas of troubles slow,
I do ascend upon this worldly stage [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
From the black kingdome of infernall Dis [...]
And from the dungen of the darke abysse,
Wherein the Ocean Seas of troubles slowe, I doe ascend vpon this worldly stage [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Benedick:] O God, sir, here's a dish I love not! I cannot endure my Lady Tongue.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: And my prophetic soul doth truly say [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: And my Propheticke Soul doth truely say [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasPage: F3 recto; book 2, satire 7 "A Cynicke Satyre" [normalized spelling].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasPageHist: F3 recto; book 2, satire 7 "A Cynicke Satyre".
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
He's but a sponge, and shortly needs must lease
His wrong got juice, when greatness' fist shall squeeze
His liquor out.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
He's but a spunge, and shortly needes must leese
His wrong got iuyce, when greatnes fist shal squeese
His liquor out.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
Then, boyling Wrath, stern, cruell, swift, and rash,
That like a Boar her teeth doth grinde and gnash:
Whose hair doth stare, like bristled Porcupine;
Who som-times rowles her ghastly-glowing eyn,
And som-time fixtly on the ground doth glaunce,
Now bleak, then bloody in her Countenance [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Andrugio:] [...] Sing Mellida is dead, all hearts will relent
[...] in sad condolement at that heavy sound [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Andrugio:] [...] Sing Mellida is deade, all hearts will relent
in sad condolement at tha heauie sound [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Brutus:] […] Let's be sacrificers, but not butchers […].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Pistol:] O, Seigneur Dew should be a gentleman.
Perpend my words, O Seigneur Dew, and mark:
O Seigneur Dew, thou diest on point of fox, except, O
Seigneur, thou do give to me egregious ransom.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Antony:] This was the noblest Roman of them all.
All the conspirators save only he
Did that they did in envy of great Caesar.
He only in a general honest thought
And common good to all made one of them.
His life was gentle and the elements
So mix'd in him that Nature might stand up
And say to all the world "This was a man!".

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Mellida:] [...] well point our speech
With amorous kissing, kissing commas [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Mellida:] [...] weele point our speech
With amorous kissing, kissing commaes [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Titinius:] [...] By your leave, gods, this is a Roman's part.
Come, Cassius sword, and find Titinius' heart!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Soldier:] My Lord,
The battle of the Spaniards is dispersed:
Beside, I bring to you this happy news,
The worthy Duke of Boulogne long desired,
And much bewailéd for his injury,
Lives and returned about an hour since.
At his first coming, armed in complete steel,
 Challeng'd the Duke Medyna at his Tent,
And there in single combat like himself,
And like a father of his country's weal,
Hath slain that proud disturber of our peace [...].
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Soldier:] My Lord,
The battle of the Spaniards is disperst:
Beside, I bring to you this happie newes,
The worthy Duke of Bulloigne long desirde,
And much bewailed for his iniurie,
Liues and returnd about an houre since.
At his first comming, armd in complete steele,
Chaleng'd the Duke Medyna at his Tent,
And there in single combat like himselfe,
And like a father of his countreys weale,
Hath slaine that proude disturber of our peace [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Firke:] I speak it in secret, mistress Rose, and he are by this time: no not so, but shortly are to come over one another with, Can you dance the shaking of the sheets?

[Eyre:] [...] mark this old wench, my king, I danced the shaking of the sheets with her six and thirty years ago.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Firke:] Hauns shoomaker, oh yes, stay, yes I haue him, I tel you what, I speake it in secret, mistris Rose, and he are by this time: no not so, but shortly are to come ouer one another with, Can you dance the shaking of the sheetes?

[Eyre:] [...] marke this olde wench, my king, I dauncde the shaking of the sheetes with her sixe and thirtie yeares agoe

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[King Henry:] [...] We are but warriors for the working day;
Our gayness and our gilt are all besmirched
With rainy marching in the painful field.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Westmoreland:] How smooth and even they do bear themselves,
 As if allegiance in their bosoms sat
Crownèd with faith and constant loyalty.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Brutus:] [...] Ha, who comes here?
I think it is the weakness of mine eyes
That shapes this monstrous apparition.
It comes upon me. - Art thou any thing?
Art thou some god, some angel, or some devil,
That mak’st my blood cold and my hair to stare?
Speak to me what thou art.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Calphurnia:] [...] And ghosts did shriek and squeal about the streets.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [King Henry:] [...] My ransom is <span class="quote">this frail and worthless trunk</sapn> [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Polonius:] Perpend.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
Come, ye heavy states of night,
Doe my father's spirit right,
Soundings baleful let mee borrow,
Burthening my song with sorrow,
Come sorrow come her eyes that sings,
By thee turned into springs.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
Come, ye heauie states of night,
Doe my father's spirit right,
Soundings balefull let mee borrow,
Burthening my song with sorrow,
Come sorrow come hir eies that sings,
By thee turned into springs.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Claudius:] But now, my cousin Hamlet, and my son - [...]
[Hamlet:] Not so, my lord; I am too much i' the sun.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Player King:] Full thirty times hath Phoebus' cart gone round [...]

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Ghost:] [...] And duller shouldst thou be than the fat weed
That roots itself in ease on Lethe wharf [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Ophelia:] There's rosemary, that's for remembrance.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Ghost:] [...] O Hamlet, what a falling off was there!

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Ghost:] [...] And in the porches of my ears did pour
The leprous distilment [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Antonio:] Resolved hearts, time curtails night,
opportunity shakes us his foretop.
Steel your thoughts, sharp your resolve,
imbolden your spirit, grasp your swords; alarum mischief,
& with an undated brow, out scout the grim opposition
Of most menacing peril.
Hark here, proud pomp shoots mounting triumph up,
Born in loud accents to the front of Jove.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Antonio:] Resolued hearts, time curtals night, opportunity shakes us his foretop. Steel your thoughts, sharp your resolve, imbolden your spirit, grasp your swords; alarum mischief, & with an undated brow, out scout the grim opposition
Of most menacing perill.
Harke here, proud pomp shoots mounting tryumph vp,
Borne in lowde accents to the front of Jove.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Ghost:] [...] And with a sudden vigor it doth posset
And curd [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Ghost:] [...] And a most instant tetter barked about [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: (Enter Antonio with a book, Lucio, Alberto; Antonio in black)
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: Enter Antonio with a booke, Lucio, Alberto; Antonio in Blacke

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: (Enter Hamlet in black, reading a book)

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Queen:] No more!
[Hamlet:] A king of shreds and patches -
(Enter Ghost)
Save me and hover o'er me with your wings, You heavenly guards! - What would your gracious figure?
[Queen:] Alas, he's mad.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Maria:] What, my good boy, stark mad?
[Antonio:] I am not.
[Maria:] Alas, is that strange news? [...]
[Maria:] Alas my son's distraught. Sweet boy appease
Thy mutining affections.
 [Antonio:] By the astoning terror of swart night,
By the infectious damps of clammy graves,
And by the mould that presseth down
My dead father's skull: I'll be reveng'd.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Maria:] What, my good boy, stark mad?
[Antonio:] I am not.
[Maria:] Alas, is that strange news? [...]
[Maria:] Alas my son's distraught. Sweete boy appease
Thy mutining affections.
 [Antonio:] By the astonning terror of swart night,
By the infectious damps of clammie graues,
And by the mould that presseth downe
My deade fathers sculle: Ile be reueng'd.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Antonio:] [...] Blood cries for blood, and murder murder craves.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Hamlet:] What is he whose grief Bears such an emphasis, whose phrase of sorrow Conjures the wand’ring stars and makes them stand Like wonder-wounded hearers? This is I, Hamlet the Dane.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Hamlet:] [...] Roasted in wrath and fire,
And thus o'ersizèd with coagulate gore [...].

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Pandulpho:] [...] Yet I am less than a man. I am the miserables soul that breathes.
[Antonio:] 'Slid, sir, ye lie! by h'heart of grief, thou lies! I scorn't that any wretched should survive Outmounting me in that superlative: Most miserable, most unmatched woe. Who dare assume that, but Antonio?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: Camillo and Hippolito are young Venetian noblemen, just returned from the wars; Camillo brings with him a captured French gentleman named Fontinelle. Camillo turns his prisoner over to Hippolito's sister Violetta for safekeeping. Violetta is the object of Camillo's affections; but Fontinelle and Violetta fall in love. Learning of this unwelcome development, Camillo and Hippolito try to tempt Fontinelle to infidelity by sending his portrait to the courtesan Imperia, hoping to interest her in the Frenchman. The ploy fails (at first), and Camillio has Fontinelle thrown into prison. But Fontinelle and Violetta are secretly married. In the last act, however, the Venetians' plotting bears fruit: Fontinelle falls for Imperia, and Violetta has to resort to the standard Elizabethan bed trick

O zounds that I were there to answer her.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Anselme:] Mistris God saue you.

To say God saue you, is the fellow mad,

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: For, would you not (in good sooth) imagine us all to be out of our wits: if you could make us believe, that the master devil himself with all his adherents were able to make a thing essentially existing in nature, either to be or not to be, when it pleases himself?
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: For, would you not (in good sooth) imagine vs all to be out of our wits: if you could make vs beleeue, that the maister diuell himselfe with all his adherents were able to make a thing essentiallie existing in nature, eyther to be or not to be, when it pleases himselfe?

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage

[Prologue:] And hither am I come,
A prologue armed, but not in confidence
Of author's pen or actor’s voice, but suited
In like conditions as our argument,
To tell you, fair beholders, that our play
Leaps o'er the vaunt and firstlings of those broils,
Beginning in the middle, starting thence away
To what may be digested in a play.

[Northumberland:] Set forward then. (A dead march, and pass round the stage, and Guilford speaks).
The Tower will be a place of ample state,
Some lodgings in it, will like dead men's souls,
Remember us of frailty.
[Guilford:] We are led with pomp to prison,
O prophetic soul.
Lo we ascend into our chairs of State,
Like funeral Coffins, in some funeral
Pomp descending to their graves. But we must on.
How can we fare well, to keep our Court:
Where Prisoners keep their cave?
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Northumberland:] Set forward then. (A dead march, and passe round the stage, and Guilford speakes).
The Towre will be a place of ample state,
Some lodgings in it, will like dead mens souls,
Remember vs of frailty.
[Guilford:] We are led with pompe to prison,
O propheticke soule.
Lo we ascend into our chaires of State,
Like funerall Coffins, in some funerall
Pompe descending to their graues. But we must on.
How can we fare well, to keep our Court:
Where Prisoners keepe their caue?

[Malevole:] Give place. Illo, ho, ho, ho, art there old truepenny? (Exit Celso) Where hast thou spent thy self this morning? I see flattery in thine eyes, and damnation in thy soul. Ha thou huge rascal!
[Mendoza:] Thou art very merry.
[Malevole:] As a scholar futuens gratis: How doth the devil go with thee now?
[Mendoza:] Malevole, thou art an arrant knave.
[Malevole:] Who I, I have been a Sergeant man.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Malevole:] Giue place. Illo, ho, ho, ho, arte there olde true penny? (Exit Celso) Where hast thou spent thy selfe this morning? I see flattery in thine eies, and damnation in thy soule. Ha thou huge rascall!
[Mendoza:] Thou art very merry.
[Malevole:] As a scholler futuens gratis: How dooth the diuell goe with thee now?
[Mendoza:] Maleuole, thou art an arrant knaue.
[Malevole:] Who I, I haue beene a Sergeant man.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Mendoza:] O! how full of ravishing attraction is your pretty, petulant, languishing, lasciviously-composed countenance these amorous smiles, those soul-warming sparkling glances, ardent as those flames that sing'd the world by heedless Phaeton; in body how delicate, in soul how witty, in discourse how pregnant, in life how wary, in favours how iuditious, in day how sociable, and in night how?
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Mendoza:] O! how full of rauishing attraction is your prettie, petulant, langushing, laciuiously-composed countenance these amorous smiles, those soule-warming sparkling glances, ardent as those flames that sing'd the world by heedelesse Phaeton; in body how delicate, in soule how wittie, in discourse how pregnant, in life how warie, in fauours how iuditious, in day how sociable, and in night how?

To quench his thirst:
Runs to his Ink-pot, drinks, then stops the hole,
And thus grows madder, then he was at first.
Tasso, he finds, by that of Hamlet, thinks
Terms him a mad-man that of his Inkhorn drinks.
Calls players fools, the fool he judgeth wisest,
Will learn them Action out of Chaucer's Pander.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
To quench his thirst:
Runs to his Inke-pot, drinkes, then stops the hole,
And thus growes madder, then he was at first.
Tasso, he finds, by that of Hamlet, thinkes
Tearmes him a mad-man that of his Inkhorne drinks.
Calls players fooles, the foole he judgeth wisest,
Will learne them Action out of Chaucer's Pander.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Lorenzo:] <span class="quote">Such a size of humanity now, and brain enough in it, it is not in the strength of a woman to withstand; well she may hold out a parley or two, for 'tis a weak fort that obeys at the first or second summons, if she resist the third she is discharg'd, though she yield in future: for then it appears it was no fault of hers: but the man that would take no denial. What rests now? means for access: True. O an honest Bawd were worth gold now.</spanA
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Lorenzo:] Such a size of humanity now, and braine enough in it, it is not in the strength of a woman to withstand; well shee may hold out a parlee or two, for 'tis a weake fort that obeyes at the first or second summons, if shee resist the third shee is discharg'd, though shee yeeld in future: for then it appeares it was no fault of hers: but the man that would take no deniall. What rests now? meanes for accesse: True. O an honest Baude were worth gold now.

[Brabantio:] I had rather to adopt a child than get it.
Come hither, Moor.
I here do give thee that with all my heart
Which, but thou hast already, with all my heart
I would keep from thee. - For your sake, jewel,
I am glad at soul I have no other child,
For thy escape would teach me tyranny,
To hang clogs on them.

[Malheureux:] But what vow, what vow?
[Franceschina:] So long as Freevill lives, I must not love.
[Malheureux:] Then he –
[Franceschina:] Must -
[Malheureux:] Die!
[Franceschina:] Ay. - No, there is no such vehemence in your affects.

[Hercules:] A Fool?
[Zuccone:] A Coxcomb?
[Hercules:] A Ninnyhammer?
[Zuccone:] A Woodcock?
[Hercules:] A Calf?
[Zuccone:] No, she shall find that I ha' eyes.
[Hercules:] And brain.

[They lay Vangue in Syphax bed and draw the curtains]
There lie Syphax bride, a naked man is soon undressed;
There bide dishonoured passion.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Zoya:] Well, upon your apparent repentance, that all modest spectators may witness, I have for a short time only thus feignedly hated you, that you might ever after truely love me, upon these cautions I reaccept you: first you shall vow.
[Zuccone:] I do vow, as heaven bless me, I will do.
[Zoya:] What?
[Zuccone:] Whate'er it be, say on I beseech you.
[Zoya:] You shall vow.
[Zuccone:] Yes.
[Zoya:] That you shall never.
[Zuccone:] Never.
[Zoya:] Feign love to my waiting woman or chamber maid.
[Zuccone:] No.
[Zoya:] Never promise them such a farm to their marriage.
[Zuccone:] No.
[Zoya:] If she'll discover but whom I affect.
[Zuccone:] Never. [Zoya:] Or if they know none that they'll but take a false oath; I do, only to be rid of me.
[Zuccone:] I swear I will not, I will not only not counterfeit love your women, but I will truely hate them an't be possible, so far from maintaining them that I will beggar them, I will never pick their trunks for letters, search their pockets, ruffle their bosoms, or tear their foul smocks never, never.
[Zoya:] That if I chance to have a humour to be in a mask, you shall not grow Jealous.
[Zuccone:] Never.
[Zoya:] Or grudge at the expense.
[Zuccone:] Never, I will eat mine own arms first.
[Zoya:] That you shall not, search if my chamber door hinges be oiled to avoid creaking.
[Zuccone:] As I am a sensible creature-
[Zoya:] Nor ever suspect the reason why my bed-chamber floor is double matted.
[Zuccone:] Not as I have blood in me.

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: VVho would endure the mockes and scornes of the world [...] vnlesse they hoped, that after the vessel of theyr bodies were seasoned in the wombe of the earth, they should arriue at that blessed vndiscovered country, where is no mediocritie of ioy, no end of pleasure.

As mad as the vexed sea, singing aloud,
Crowned with rank fumiter and furrow-weeds,
With hardocks, hemlock, nettles, cuckooflowers,
Darnel, and all the idle weeds that grow
In our sustaining corn.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText:
[Duchess:] Was't ever known stepduchess was so mild
And calm as I? Some now would plot his death,
With easy doctors, those loose-living men,
And make His withered Grace fall to his grave
And keep church better.
Some second wife would do this, and dispatch
Her double loathèd lord at meat and sleep.
Indeed, 'tis true an old man's twice a childe,
Mine cannot speak; one of his single words,
Would quite have freed my youngest dearest son
From death or durance, and have made him walk
With a bold foote vpon the thorny law,
Whose prickles should bow under him, but 'tis not,
And therefore wedlock faith shall be forgot,
I'll kill him in his forehead, hate there feed,
That wound is deepest though it neuer bleed.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Dutchesse:] Wast euer knowne step-Dutchesse was so milde,
And calme as I? some now would plot his death,
With easie Doctors, those loose liuing men,
And make his witherd Grace fall to his Graue,
And keepe Church better?
Some second wife would do this, and dispatch
Her double loathd Lord at meate and sleepe,
Indeed 'tis true an old mans twice a childe,
Mine cannot speake, one of his single words,
Would quite haue freed my yongest deerest sonne
From death or durance, and haue made him walke
With a bold foote vpon the thornie law,
Whose Prickles should bow vnder him, but 'tis not,
And therefore wedlock faith shall be forgot,
Ile kill him in his fore-head, hate there feede,
That wound is deepest tho it neuer bleed [...].

[Duke of Millain]: How old are you?
[Lazarello]: Full eight and twenty several Almanacks
Hath been compiled, all for several years
Since first I drew this breath; four apprenticeships
Have I most truly served in this world:
And eight and twenty times hath Phoebus Cart
Run out his yearly course since -
[Duke]: I understand you Sir.
[Lucio]: How like an ignorant Poet he talks.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist:
[Duke of Millain]: How old are you?
[Lazarello]: Full eight and twenty severall Almanackes
Hath been compiyed, all for severall yeares
Since first I drew this breath; foure prentiships
Have I most truly served in this world:
And eight and twenty times hath Phoebus Carre
Runne out his yearely course since -
[Duke]: I understand you Sir.
[Lucio]: How like an ignorant Poet he talkes.

[Oriana]: I thank you good Brother: and if you doubt of the cause of my coming I can Satisfy you.
[Count]: No faith, I dare trust thee, I do suspect thou art honest; for it is so rare a thing to be honest amongst you, that some one man in an age, may perhaps suspect some two women to be honest, but never believe it verily.

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Maria:] Go fetch my ladder of Ropes, Leander's come.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Graccus:] Excellent, for now must he needs fall into the Constable's hands: and if he have any grace, t'will appear in his face, when he shall be carried through the street in a white sheet t'will be a good penance for his fault.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Graccus:] Excellent, for now must he needes fall into the Constables hands: and if he haue any grace, twil appear in his face, when he shall be carried through the streete in a white sheet twill be a good penance for his fault.

p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Gudgin:] Ere long he will take up his station at a Stationers, where we shall see him do penance in a Sheet at least.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Gudgin:] Ere long hee will take vp his station at a Stationers, where wee shall see him doe pennaunce in a Sheete at least.

p0826-teimww:passage.knoraXmlImport:label: passage
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasText: [Flamineo:] Let me see, it is more than time that I commit this divine pill to his hopeful working: least my staff be out of the rest when my adversary is in the carrier.
p0826-teimww:passage.p0826-teimww:hasTextHist: [Flamineo:] Let me see, it is more then time that I commit this deuine pill to his hopefull working: least my staffe be out of the rest when my aduersary is in the carriere.
